items.synopsis: King Charles and Queen Camilla join big crowds at Windsor Castle for the coronation concert, while people across the UK also gather together to celebrate at home. Follow live.

title.children: A dancing duchess, a heartfelt message to 'Pa', but a lack of Louis at coronation concert

schema.headline: King's coronation concert live updates: Lionel Richie, Katy Perry get royal family dancing

liveBlogUpdate.headline: We'll wrap up our live coverage here
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Thank you for joining us. You can navigate the key moments from the coronation concert with our key events tab. Find the latest news here on the ABC News website and on our app. You can also download the ABC News app and subscribe to our range of news alerts.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Wondering where to watch the concert?
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Unfortunately, the coronation concert wasn't played live in Australia, but there is a replay tonight. You'll find that on channel 7 from 7.30 pm.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Here's what Olly Murs and Nicole Scherzinger said about performing
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: We've already heard from these two artists, but here's a video of them foreshadowing their performances as they arrived:

liveBlogUpdate.headline: The concert was a different feel to the rest of the celebrations
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: This is a great celebration after the coronation of King Charles, Saturday was deeply religious, now its time to celebrate. - Ruth McCue. Hey Ruth, That's a wrap for the concert, it was definitely more upbeat than anything else we've seen over the weekend.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: The crowds are no joke
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Imagine having a backyard this big:

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Mark Owen performs Shine
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Mark Owen has performed Shine on stage as the show starts to wrap up.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: WIndsor Castle lights up with drone show
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The drones are in full force above the stage.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: What was Katy Perry's performance like?
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Katy Perry roars onto the stage in a golden gown. The crowd is having a great time. "I am so happy to celebrate this whole weekend," she says. She also tells the crowd she's staying in Windsor Castle. Next up is Firework, which she dedicates to King Charles.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: The Duke and Duchess of Edinburgh get their groove on
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: It's hard not to have a boogie to Lionel Richie performing All Night Long. The Duke and Duchess of Edinburgh, Prince Edward and Sophie, are clearly fans.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Celebrity sketches break up the music acts
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Tom Cruise, Bear Grylls, English actor and author Dame Joan Collins, and Welsh singer Tom Jones are expected to feature in sketches aired this morning. Winnie the Pooh is also set to make an appearance, perhaps in an attempt to top Paddington Bear 's meeting with Queen Elizabeth II at her Jubilee Party at the Palace concert last year .

liveBlogUpdate.headline: The royal children are having a great time
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Princess Charlotte, in particular, appears to be loving the performances. Prince Louis isn't at the concert but I just know he's dancing along at home.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Landmarks across the UK light up
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: There are celebrations across the UK and landmarks are being lit up across the region as Paloma Faith performs Lullaby.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Prince William shares heartfelt message to his 'Pa'
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Unfortunately, we won't be getting a performance out of Prince William, but he has some words to share about his father. "As my grandmother said when she was crowned, coronations are a declaration of our hopes for the future," he says. He says the late Queen Elizabeth would be a proud mother this weekend. King Charles has dedicated himself to serving others, Prince William says. 'Pa, we're all so proud of you," he says. The crowd recites "God save the King" after Prince William.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: A standing ovation for Lionel Richie
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The Royals are on their feet to cheer on LIonel Richie, even King Charles himself.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Lionel Richie's performance receives standing ovation
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: It's easy like a Sunday morning for Lionel Richie, who is sitting in front of a piano in this stripped-back performance. Next up he's ditched the instrument to sing All Night Long. There's a standing ovation after his performance, even from the royals.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: King Charles 'the artist formally known as Prince'
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: In his introduction earlier, Hugh Boneville joked that King Charles was the artist formally known as Prince. Here's how it was received by the king himself:

liveBlogUpdate.headline: We can expect a few collabs too
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: A number of collaborative performances are scheduled, including Italian opera star Andrew Bocelli, who will perform a duet with Welsh bass-baritone Sir Bryn Terfel. Self-proclaimed lifelong monarchist Steve Winwood, of Traffic, Blind Faith and Spencer Davis Group fame, will perform alongside a virtual choir as well as a spoken-word performance by Bollywood actress Sonam Kapoor. Nicole Scherzinger of the Pussycat Dolls and pianist Lang Lang will perform together, while London singer-songwriter Freya Ridings will perform with composer and pianist Alexis Ffrench. Among others confirmed to perform are Olly Murs, Paloma Faith and Tiwa Savage.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Miss Piggy and Kermit are late to the concert
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Nigerian singer Tiwa Savage has just performed Keys to the Kingdom and now the show is being interrupted by Miss Piggy and Kermit the Frog. Miss Piggy's looking for a way to marry a lord so that she can become a lady.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Bring me a higher love!
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: There's now a performance of Higher Love from Steve Winwood recognising all of the commonwealth countries. The massive crowd is having a ball. Of course, we Aussies got a little recognition in this performance.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Katy Perry and Lionel Richie are among a line-up of international performers
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: According to Town and Country magazine, acts to take part are pop star Katy Perry, who turned heads at the coronation ceremony on Saturday in her pink outfit, as well as fellow American singer Lionel Richie. Nineties UK boy band Take That are the biggest British pop stars to be confirmed for the event. Band members Gary Barlow, Howard Donald and Mark Owen are all scheduled to perform their first live show since 2019 in front of Windsor Castle. However, we're not yet sure whether former Take That member Robbie Williams is set to entertain.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Rapid-fire performances
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: We've just heard from the Coronation Choir and then pianist Lang Lang took the stage. Mr Lang, no stranger to prestigious events including the Queen's Diamond Jubilee, said the evening would be really special "like a fairytale." "To play in front of this Windsor Castle it's a really big honour. And especially this is a special moment," he said. Performances are moving quickly, Nicole Scherzinger is now performing a version of Christina Agulera's Reflection.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: There are huge crowds at Windsor Castle
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Here's what it looks like:

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Olly Murs takes the stage
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The concert kicked off with a performance of Rudimental's Feel The Love. We're now hearing from actor Hugh Bonneville who is introducing Olly Murs to the stage who will perform Dance With Me tonight.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: King Charles has arrived for his coronation concert
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Good morning, welcome to our live coverage of the King's coronation concert and celebrations across the UK. More than 20,000 people have arrived at Windsor Castle to watch a star-studded lineup including Lionel Richie and Katy Perry. King Charles and Queen Consort have taken their seats, so let's get started.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: What's in the $14.6 billion cost of living package in the budget?
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Let's unpack what's going to be one of the centrepieces of the federal government's budget tomorrow night. One of the key measures that makes up this $14.6 billion relief package over four years includes a $1.5 billion energy bill subsidy for more than 5 million households and 1 million small businesses. Those eligible (pensioners, small businesses, and those on income support) will receive up to $500 relief on their power bills, but the size of the assistance depends on where you live. You can hear more about the energy bill relief package in tomorrow night's budget here:

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Westpac records $4 billion net profit in half-year results
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Westpac is the latest major bank to post its half-yearly results, recording a $4 billion net profit — up 22% compared to this time last year. The bank is also increasing dividends to 70 cents per share, an increase of 15%. Westpac says the increase to its net profit was boosted by improving margins, thanks to rising interest rates and growth in home and business loans.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: ASX set to open higher on federal budget eve
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Good morning and welcome to another week — it's Monday, May 8 and budget eve. If you're as excited as I am about the budget (you are on a markets and financial blog, after all) you'll have keenly spotted the federal government is out spruiking a near- $15 billion cost of living package to be unveiled in tomorrow night's budget. The $14.6 billion support package over four years is aimed to ease pressure on households and businesses, including $1.5 billion for electricity bill relief for 5.5 million households and 1 million small businesses. (I'll unpack what we know about the relief package shortly.) On the markets front, we can expect the local sharemarket to open higher with ASX futures up, and greater investor sentiment thanks to all three major benchmarks gaining. Investors are also waiting for Westpac's half yearly results, which have just dropped as I post this. Let's get into it, shall we?
